<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1153,2045]" lastBlockId="22.[151,1436,153,324]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1981,2008]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Comments.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alencar &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2020" box="[629,790,1983,2009]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eura">
<emphasis box="[629,790,1983,2009]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Apenesia eura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the pronotum long; the notaulus complete and parallel; the hypopygium with a flap and the posterior margin strongly concave, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alencar &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2020" box="[1136,1235,2018,2045]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="farela">
<emphasis box="[1136,1235,2018,2045]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">A. farela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the mesoscu- tum-mesoscutellar suture wide; the metapostnotum irregularly foveolate anteriorly; the cuspis with two apical calli, ventral one larger than the dorsal with dorsal end short, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alencar &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2020" box="[880,963,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eura">
<emphasis box="[880,963,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">A. eura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the mesoscutum-mesoscutellar suture narrow; the metapostnotum v-shaped and rugulose; the cuspis with three apical calli, almost equally sized with the dorsal end short.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
